<subSubSection id="C34A6528FFE4FFC4A5F8FA871F28FB41" lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="22" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BEF36A3FFE4FFC5A5F8FA871B0BFA25" blockId="20.[136,1452,1374,2013]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis id="B924EAB1FFE4FFC5A5F8FA871C3AFAB8" bold="true" box="[189,517,1374,1401]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Distribution and habitat:—</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C504D20FFE4FFC5A740FA861CB8FAB8" authorityName="N. E. Brown ex Britton &amp; P. Wilson" authorityYear="1925" baseAuthorityName="Miller" box="[517,647,1374,1400]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Verbenaceae" genus="Lippia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="alba">
<emphasis id="B924EAB1FFE4FFC5A740FA861CB8FAB8" box="[517,647,1374,1400]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Lippia alba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distributed from the South of the 
<collectingCountry id="F3477633FFE4FFC5A15EFA871A8EFAB9" box="[1051,1201,1374,1401]" name="United States of America" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">United States</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry id="F3477633FFE4FFC5A196FA871B7DFAB8" box="[1235,1346,1374,1400]" name="Argentina" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Argentina</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFC14B52FFE4FFC5A014FA871EFCFA5D" author="Sanders, R. W." pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="303 - 358" refId="ref38609" refString="Sanders, R. W. (2001) The genera of Verbenaceae in the southeastern United States. Harvard Papers in Botany 5: 303 - 358." type="journal article" year="2001">Sanders 2001</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC14B52FFE4FFC5A58AFA5B1F81FA5D" author="Salimena, F. R. G. &amp; Ferreira, S. C. &amp; Cardoso, P. H. &amp; Valerio, V. I. R." box="[207,446,1410,1437]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" refId="ref38216" refString="Salimena, F. R. G., Ferreira, S. C., Cardoso, P. H. &amp; Valerio, V. I. R. (2016) Verbenaceae. In: Rizzo, J. A. (Org.) Flora dos estados de Goias e Tocantins. CEGRAF-UFG, Goiania, 157 pp." type="book" year="2016">
Salimena 
<emphasis id="B924EAB1FFE4FFC5A47AFA5A1F46FA5C" box="[319,377,1410,1436]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
). It is the widest distributed species of the genus in Brazilian territory and is found in all states and phytogeographic domains (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC14B52FFE4FFC5A774FA7F1D5DFA01" author="Salimena, F. R. G. &amp; Cardoso, P. H." box="[561,866,1446,1473]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" refId="ref37937" refString="Salimena, F. R. G. &amp; Cardoso, P. H. (2020) Lippia in Flora do Brasil 2020 under construction. Jardim Botanico do Rio de Janeiro. Available from: http: // floradobrasil. jbrj. gov. br / reflora / floradobrasil / FB 15170 (accessed 4 January 2021)" type="url" year="2020">Salimena &amp; Cardoso 2020</bibRefCitation>
), besides being very cultivated. In Espírito Santo, it occurs in seasonal semideciduous forest, dense rainforest, and ciliar forest. Not found in SPAs in this state.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEF36A3FFE4FFC5A5F8FA361AB6F9C8" blockId="20.[136,1452,1374,2013]" box="[189,1161,1518,1545]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis id="B924EAB1FFE4FFC5A5F8FA361F60F9C9" bold="true" box="[189,351,1519,1545]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Phenology:—</emphasis>
Collected with flowers in May, July, and October and with fruits in July.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEF36A3FFE4FFC5A5F8F9CB1C1AF9B5" blockId="20.[136,1452,1374,2013]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis id="B924EAB1FFE4FFC5A5F8F9CB1CBCF9ED" bold="true" box="[189,643,1554,1581]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Preliminary conservation assessment:</emphasis>
—This is a common species, presents wide distribution (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC14B52FFE4FFC5A04CF9CB1B98F9ED" author="Sanders, R. W." box="[1289,1447,1554,1581]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="303 - 358" refId="ref38609" refString="Sanders, R. W. (2001) The genera of Verbenaceae in the southeastern United States. Harvard Papers in Botany 5: 303 - 358." type="journal article" year="2001">Sanders 2001</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC14B52FFE4FFC5A5CDF9EF1F48F991" author="Salimena, F. R. G. &amp; Ferreira, S. C. &amp; Cardoso, P. H. &amp; Valerio, V. I. R." box="[136,375,1590,1617]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" refId="ref38216" refString="Salimena, F. R. G., Ferreira, S. C., Cardoso, P. H. &amp; Valerio, V. I. R. (2016) Verbenaceae. In: Rizzo, J. A. (Org.) Flora dos estados de Goias e Tocantins. CEGRAF-UFG, Goiania, 157 pp." type="book" year="2016">
Salimena 
<emphasis id="B924EAB1FFE4FFC5A5BCF9EE1F0DF990" box="[249,306,1590,1616]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
), being recorded inside protected areas in South America, and is widest cultivated. Considered “Least Concern” (LC) (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC14B52FFE4FFC5A4CAF9821C25F9B5" author="IUCN Standards &amp; Petitions Committee" box="[399,538,1627,1653]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" refId="ref34955" refString="IUCN Standards and Petitions Committee (2019) Guidelines for Using the IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria. Version 14. Available from: http: // www. iucnredlist. org / documents / RedListGuidelines. pdf (accessed 30 December 2019)" type="book" year="2019">IUCN 2019</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
